\begin_layout Section
Coarsening
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 be the latent data,
 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 an arbitrary random variable,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X=(\phi(Z,D),D)$
\end_inset

 be the observed data.
 The function 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is a known 
\emph on
coarsening
\emph default
 function.
 The observations satisfy coarsening at random if 
\begin_inset Formula $p(d\mid z)=p(d\mid z')$
\end_inset

 whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(z,d)=\phi(z',d)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\log p(z,r)=\log p(z)+\log p(r),
\]

\end_inset

Here 
\begin_inset Formula $p(r)$
\end_inset

 is a distribution over 
\begin_inset Formula $\{0,1\}^{R}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{t}$
\end_inset

 be a path with score function 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\log p(z,r)=\log p(z)+g,
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Score and information operators
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}=\{P_{\eta}\mid\eta\in H\}$
\end_inset

,
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 capital 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

,
 not a Hilbert space.
 Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 is a space of probability measures.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We wish to estimate 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi(\eta)=\psi(P_{\eta})$
\end_inset

,
 e.g.,
 an agreement coefficient from 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta=(Q,R)$
\end_inset

 after data coarsening.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\eta}(H)$
\end_inset

 be the tangent space of 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{P_{\eta}}(\mathcal{P})$
\end_inset

 be the other tangent space.
 Suppose that each smooth path 
\begin_inset Formula $t\to\eta_{t}$
\end_inset

 induces a smooth path 
\begin_inset Formula $t\to P_{\eta_{t}}$
\end_inset

.
 Then we have a pairing 
\begin_inset Formula $(b,g)$
\end_inset

 of score functions that induces a linear operator
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g=A_{\eta}b,
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

We assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\eta}$
\end_inset

 is continuous and linear.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Ok.
 So the operator exists anyway,
 and but is only linear if 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\eta}(H)$
\end_inset

 is a linear space.
 And we assume its bounded.
 Alright,
 it's always extended to a linear operator.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We do not assume 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{\eta}$
\end_inset

 is onto 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{P_{\eta}}(\mathcal{P})$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We need to solve
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A_{\eta}^{*}\tilde{\psi}_{P_{\eta}}=\tilde{\chi}_{\eta},
\]

\end_inset

which requires that 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\chi}_{\eta}\in R(A_{\eta}^{*})$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\ker T=R(T^{*})^{\bot}$
\end_inset

,
 there is a unique solution in 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\text{span}A_{\eta}T_{\eta}(H)}$
\end_inset

 if a solution exists.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in R(T^{*}T)$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{*}x=y$
\end_inset

 has a solution.
 Indeed,
 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{*}x=T^{*}Tz$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
T^{*}x & = & y\\
Ty & = & x
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Hmmm...
 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{ker}T=R(T^{*})^{\bot}$
\end_inset

:
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in\ker T$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $0=\left\langle Tx,y\right\rangle =\left\langle x,T^{*}y\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is orthogonal to the range of 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 This goes both ways so we have equality.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $(T^{*}T)^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

 satisfy 
\begin_inset Formula $(T^{*}T)^{\dagger}$
\end_inset

 (return to this – this is general Hilbert space theory I feel I should master – redo Analysis Now and make notes.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Estimation goal
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We need to make more assumptions perhaps.
 In particular,
 we need to restrict ourselves to models where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E\left[\binom{\mathcal{R}}{k}^{-1}\sum_{j}l^{k}(X_{j_{1}},X_{j_{2}},\ldots,X_{j_{k}})R_{j_{1}}\cdots R_{j_{k}}\right]=d,
\]

\end_inset

as this will encode the whole MCAR assumption.
 On the other hand,
 it 
\emph on
seems
\emph default
 the estimator is efficient under PMCAR and PMCAR 
\emph on
only
\emph default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It's probably better 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d=\binom{\mathcal{R}}{2}^{-1}\sum_{j<k}E_{X^{\star}\sim Q}l(X_{j}^{\star},X_{k}^{\star})
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi(X_{i}^{*},R_{i})=\binom{\mathcal{R}}{2}^{-1}\sum_{j<k}\frac{R_{ij}R_{ik}}{\pi_{jk}}(l(X_{ij}^{*},X_{ik}^{*})-d_{jk})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Efficient score functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{l}_{\theta,\eta}$
\end_inset

 be the score for 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta$
\end_inset

 is fixed.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\tilde{l}_{\theta,\eta} & = & (1-\Pi_{\theta,\eta})\dot{l}_{\theta,\eta},\\
\tilde{I}_{\theta,\eta} & = & P_{\theta,\eta}\tilde{l}_{\theta,\eta}\tilde{l}_{\theta,\eta}^{T}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Score and information operators
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 be indexed by 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta\in H$
\end_inset

.
 Define 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(P_{\eta})=\chi(\eta)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi:H\to\mathbb{R}^{k}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g=A_{\eta}b
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tilde{\psi}_{P_{\eta}}=A_{\eta}(A_{\eta}^{*}A_{\eta})^{-}\tilde{\chi}_{\eta}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Notes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 be a space of distributions dominated by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi:\mathcal{P}\to\mathbb{R}^{k}$
\end_inset

 a functional.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{t}^{1/2}$
\end_inset

 is Fréchet differentiable in 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

visualize
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the tangent set as 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{2}gp^{1/2}$
\end_inset

,
 i.e.,
 the score function evaluated at 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 be a space of distributions dominated by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi:\mathcal{P}\to\mathbb{R}^{k}$
\end_inset

 a functional.
 Where 
\begin_inset Formula $t\to p_{t}^{1/2}$
\end_inset

 is Hadamard differentiable in 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 be a space of densities dominated by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p=\frac{dP}{d\mu}\in\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

.
 A 
\emph on
tangent
\emph default
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is a map 
\begin_inset Formula $t\to p_{t}^{1/2}$
\end_inset

 defined on 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,\epsilon)$
\end_inset

 that 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
is Hadamard differentiable in 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{2}$
\end_inset

 with derivative 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 called the 
\emph on
score function
\emph default
,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}=p$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Definition
The tangent set is the set of all tangents to 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

.
 (Actually it's the 
\emph on
scores
\emph default
 we care about,
 not the paths.) 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
The functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 is differentiable at 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 relative to 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\mathcal{P}}_{P}$
\end_inset

 if there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\psi}:L_{2}(P)\to\mathbb{R}^{k}$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\psi(P_{t})-\psi(P)}{t}\to\dot{\psi}_{P}g
\]

\end_inset

for all paths 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{t}$
\end_inset

 with score 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

.
 I.e.,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(P)=\psi(P_{t})+t\dot{\psi}_{P}g+o(t)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We may write 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{\psi}g=\left\langle \tilde{\psi},g\right\rangle _{P}=\int\tilde{\psi}gdP$
\end_inset

 by the Riesz representation theorem.
 But we may find 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\psi}\in\overline{\text{span}\mathcal{\dot{\mathcal{P}}}_{P}}$
\end_inset

 this is unique and called the 
\emph on
efficient influence function.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is the projection of any influence function on the closed span of the tangent set.
 
\end_layout

